<DOCNO> AP900609-0006 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
defense secretary dick cheney responding to 
concerns that shortrange nuclear missiles could leak plutonium is 
ordering air force bombers to stop carrying older missiles until 
safety studies are completed 
cheney said in a statement friday he was taking the step as a 
precaution 
the directors of three us nuclear weapons laboratories called 
for the withdrawal of the weapons during congressional testimony 
last month they suggested there was a remote possibility the 
weapons could leak plutonium in an accident 
the missiles are known as the shortrange attack missilea or 
sramas and are carried aboard the nations 372 deployed b52 b1b 
and fb111 bombers the air force has said that 1500 of the weapons 
were produced between 1971 and 1975 but the current number deployed 
is classified 
sen james exon dneb chairman of the armed services strategic 
forces subcommittee which heard the lab directors testimony 
agreed with the move 
there was really nothing else the secretary could do said 
exon who was interviewed on cable news network 
cheneys statement said the weapons would not be placed on board 
bombers on ground alert the warplanes that are loaded with 
weapons fueled and ready to fly to war if necessary within 
minutes the number of aircraft on such alert is classified 
the weapons will be removed from the bombers pending the outcome 
of air force and energy department safety studies expected to be 
completed this summer the pentagon statement said the energy 
department is in charge of nuclear weapons 
cheney decided to remove the weapons after discussions with 
energy secretary james watkins the directors of the three 
laboratories and after receiving additional information about 
the srama the statement said it did not elaborate on what that 
information might have been 
the srama is not the only nuclear weapon carried by bombers the 
planes also carry a complement of longerrange nuclear missiles and 
freefall bombs a new model shortrange missile designated sram2 
is under development for deployment in 1993 
the 14foot long srama is an airtosurface missile armed with 
the w69 nuclear warhead with an estimated explosive yield 
equivalent to 170000 tons of tnt which is 11 to 13 times the power 
of the bomb that destroyed hiroshima in 1945 
some nuclear specialists have suggested it would be used against 
targets that threatened the bombers themselves such as radar 
stations fighter bases and antiaircraft missile sites up to 100 
miles away 
the safety of the missile warhead was reviewed in 1989 and 
because of that review some procedures for handling the weapons 
were modified 
the laboratories have initiated new analyses until those 
analyses are complete i believe it is prudent to take this 
action the statement quoted cheney as saying the srama poses 
no safety hazards to the public 
house speaker tom foley dwash called the move correct and 
prudent 
the international strategic conditions have changed 
dramatically in the last year as well and were not in the same 
condition of need for as widespread an alert status as was 
previously the case he added 
in their testimony may 23 the three laboratory directors said 
the missile might be vulnerable to an accidental explosion of the 
missile fuel that could disperse the highly toxic plutonium of the 
weapon 
an accident such as a fire or crash could not detonate the 
plutonium they said 
the directors were john nuckolls of the lawrence livermore 
national laboratory in california sigfried hecker of the los alamos 
national laboratory in new mexico and albert narath of sandia 
national laboratories in new mexico 
the withdrawal of the srama follows cheneys disclosure in late 
may that a safety problem existed with us nuclear artillery shells 
in europe but that it had been fixed and a risk of accidental 
nuclear explosions never materialized 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

