<TEXT>
as polarized southern baptists converge for 
their annual convention a church historian said the grand 
compromise that has held the denomination together for 145 years 
is falling apart 
its amazing that the denomination has lasted as long as it did 
intact considering its heritage of individualism and diversity 
said bill j leonard a professor at southern baptist theological 
seminary in louisville ky 
denominationalists have been masters at maintaining the 
balance despite repeated attempts through the years to upset it 
ever since the denomination was founded in 1845 he said in a 
telphone interview 
since then the broad compact that affirmed classic christian 
beliefs while allowing varied interpretations has held together 
but now with the diffusion of southern culture and steps by the 
controlling fundamentalist wing to draw narrower lines of 
thought the old inclusive coalition is crumbling he said 
about 35000 messengers from churches across the country were 
expected for the convention opening tuesday in the louisiana 
superdome preceded by rival pastors conferences running through 
monday 
leonard foresaw no abrupt denominational breakup regardless of 
how the voting turns out between fundamentalist and moderate 
factions but he predicted spreading fragmentation of the 
149millionmember denomination the nations largest protestant 
body 
leonard details his analysis in a book gods last and only 
hope the fragmentation of the southern baptist convention 
it offers the most comprehensive treatment yet of a conflict that 
began in 1979 when fundamentalists launched a drive to purge the 
denomination of liberal tendencies and personnel 
that faction which insists on a literalistic view of the bible 
and various rightwing social positions has dominated annual 
conventions for 11 years gradually achieving majorities of trustees 
of denominational agencies and seminaries 
the fight centers on election of the denominations president 
who indirectly controls selection of trustees 
fudamentalists are backing the rev morris chapman pastor of 
first baptist church of wichita falls texas moderates support the 
rev daniel vestal pastor of dunwoody baptist church in suburban 
atlanta 
in his book leonard the 44yearold head of the faculty 
organization at the denominations oldest flagship seminary in 
louisville calls the struggle the controversy 
it has polarized almost ever segment of convention life 
leonard writes with fundamentalists denounced as totalitarians 
and hit men and moderates condemned as skunks and 
termites undermining right belief 
noting that virtually all southern baptists are theological 
conservatives affirming biblical authority leonard says 
fundamentalists seek a particular doctrinal uniformity grounded 
primarily in the dogma of biblical inerrancy 
that theory holds that the bible is without error about history 
science religion and all other matters 
many moderates also hold a fundamentalist view of scripture as 
do both presidential candidates but leonard points out moderates 
oppose efforts to impose such dogmas on the entire denomination 
in the past occasional doctrinal disputes passed because a 
prevailing southern culture held diverse views together leonard 
writes 
that unity was grounded in the grand compromise in which 
ideologues on the right or left were not allowed to control the 
center he says adding 
the denomination became a means of uniting those of various 
regional theological and liturgical traditions and holding at bay 
those who sought to impose a narrower doctrinal or ecclesiastical 
norms on the entire body 
despite recurrent temporary disputes he says the denomination 
became one of the most most organized efficient numerically 
successful ecclesiastical bodies in north america 
but with the fading of the distinctive southern identity that for 
so long held the denomination together leonard says the new drive 
for conformity in belief has shattered the old coaliton 
fundamentalists sought to establish a more explicitly 
theological identity for the denomination and insure conformity 
leonard writes those who do not accept their formulas and 
definitions are excluded from representation on convention boards of 
trustees 
their efforts have narrowed the theological parameters of the 
sbc considerably and upset the delicate balance that the 
denomination had so long struggled with amazing success to 
maintain 
unlike past disputes he says only the current controversy has 
featured an attempt to appoint people of a single ideological 
persuasion to convention boards and agencies until now convention 
appointments reflected a wide diversity of perspectives 
he says moderates continue to believe the pendulum will swing 
back to the conservative center while fundamentalists believe they 
can maintain the old denominational triumphalism and success and 
control the old coalition after having destroyed it 
unity seems impossible but separation seems unthinkable he 
concludes intrigue and inertia triumph southern baptists 
approach the 21st century having squandered much of their spiritual 
vitality and their considerable resources on a controvery in which 
they turned in on themselves rather than confront a complex world 
</TEXT>
