sen dave durenbergers finances go under a 
public microscope tuesday as the senate ethics committee holds its 
first hearings in nine years on whether a lawmaker abused his office 
the committee scheduled two grueling weeks of triallike 
proceedings that could have enormous political consequences for the 
minnesota republican whose term runs through 1994 
there would be pressure on him to quit if the committee found 
serious wrongdoing minnesota republican chairman robert weinholzer 
said in an interview that would allow democratic gov rudy perpich 
to appoint a democrat to the seat 
the ethics committee has found substantial credible evidence 
that durenberger broke senate rules or federal law in transactions 
involving his former minneapolis condominium and a book promotion 
deal 
free limousine rides for personal trips accepted from groups 
interested in legislation also may have been improper the 
committee said 
