shortly after the prime minister came to power in december 1988 
india and pakistan began talks aimed at normalizing relations that 
process was suspended during the 1989 indian elections which led to 
a change of government 
india and pakistan have been uneasy neighbors since they were 
created by the 1947 partition that ended british colonial rule of 
the subcontinent they routinely accuse each of inciting ethnic and 
religious violence in each others territory 
new delhi accuses pakistan of arming and training secessionists 
in the border states of punjab and jammukashmir indias only 
moslem state 
islamabad denies the allegations and accuses india of stirring 
trouble in the southern border province of sindh where ethnic 
bloodshed and ganglandstyle warfare have left more than 400 people 
dead in the past month 
the violence which has faded and flared for more than a decade 
is blamed on native sindhis and mohajirs or moslem indians who 
immigrated to pakistan following the partition and now dominate 
sindhs two largest cities karachi and hyderabad 
late last month ms bhutto was forced to call out the army to 
help restore law and order a move that has heightened fears that 
pakistan may soon return to military rule for the third time in its 
43year history 
ms bhutto said pakistans constitution allows the military to be 
called in to help the civilian government keep law and order 
the military is called time and again to aid the civil 
government this is their constitutional duty and this is their 
obligation to the elected government she said 
