the countrys first free election 
in 44 years should have been a joyous celebration of democracy but 
it has been marred by the legacy of its communist past 
the charges and countercharges over purported links between 
peoples party chairman josef bartoncik and the communists are the 
latest illustration of how the atmosphere of suspicion spawned by 
decades of authoritarian rule can poison the climate of emerging 
eastern european democraties 
in bartonciks case opponents have charged he collaborated for 
17 years with the communists dreaded stb secret police 
he has denied wrongdoing interior minister richard sacher also 
a member of the bartonciks noncommunist party asserted saturday 
that no evidence has been presented to back up the accusations 
thousands of files listing stb informants were destroyed in the 
aftermath of the peaceful november revolution that overturned 
communist domination bartonciks accusers say documents relating to 
bartoncik appear to have been among them 
but the staff of president vaclav havel asserts bartoncik did not 
