<TEXT>
the presidential candidate voters choose sunday 
to lead peru through the next five years will inherit a violent 
bankrupt country many people believe is ungovernable 
whatever the campaign promises longbrewing crises will make it 
difficult just to maintain current levels of poverty and popular 
discontent 
on the eve of the election maoist shining path guerrillas called 
armed strikes in four important cities in the andean highlands 
and the eastern jungle region to block the voting the call issued 
in pamphlets crudely painted wall posters and messages to radio 
station carried with it the threat of violence against those 
disobeying the order to boycott the election 
those voting will decide between novelist mario vargas llosa a 
conservative champion of free markets and alberto fujimori the son 
of japanese immigrants who was an obscure agricultural engineer 
when the presidential campaign began 
fujimori 51 and vargas llosa 54 were in a dead heat in the 
runoff election according to independent polls released friday by 
law president alan garcia cant run for a consecutive fiveyear term 
its a fallacy to say this country is ungovernable fujimori 
an independent said in an interview the country is governable 
but the political parties have demonstrated theyre incapable of 
governing 
about 10 million of the 22 million peruvians are eligible to 
vote and are required by law to do so polls will be open from 8 
am to 3 pm if it is a close contest as expected the result may 
not be known for weeks because of poor communications with isolated 
mountain and jungle towns 
the runoff was required after no candidate received a majority in 
the first round of balloting april 8 
the winner is to take office july 28 among his problems will be 
annual inflation of 2000 percent the inti worth 7 cents when 
it was introduced in 1986 has shrunk to less than twothousandths 
of a penny wages have lost 50 percent of their purchasing power in 
the past two years 
two leftist insurgencies political violence takes nine lives a 
day and at least 18500 have been killed in the last decade the 
economic damage is more than 15 billion rebels control large parts 
of the interior and onethird of peru is under military control 
a foreign debt of 20 billion the highest per capita in south 
america international agencies stopped credit when peru ceased 
making payments on the debt in 1986 and several foreign banks are 
suing the treasury is more than 100 million in the red 
labor and public unrest street sweepers prison inmates even 
hospital patients hold strikes and protests for higher pay and 
better services four of five peruvians lack regular employment 
drug trafficking peru is the largest producer of coca leaf the 
raw material of cocaine and more than 200000 peruvians make their 
living from it the international crackdown on trafficking has cut 
into the 1 billion the country earns annually from the trade and 
the united states is pressing peru to accept military aid in 
fighting coca production 
destroyed or wornout public facilities major highways are 
crumbling for lack of maintenance crippling the transport of 
produce from farms in the interior guerrillas blow up bridges and 
power lines power and water rationing hamper industrial production 
natural disasters have done their share of damage 
an earthquake devastated towns in the northern jungle last month 
and a volcano in the southern andes is threatening to erupt 
scientists have detected the beginnings of an el nino phenomenon 
unusually warm ocean currents that disrupt weather patterns a 1982 
el nino ruined crops and nearly destroyed the important fishing 
industry 
a recent rand corp study financed partly by the us state 
department said a military takeover was imminent 
conditions will become much worse before they get better it 
said the real question is not whether there will be a coup but 
when 
the general belief in peru appears to be that a fujimori victory 
would be more likely to provoke a coup because of his economic 
plans critics say they differ little from the populist measures of 
president garcia 
among fujimoris stated goals are reducing annual inflation to 
less than 100 percent by the end of his first year he advocates 
maintaining controls on the economy which vargas llosa blames for 
perus economic decline and says he will replace the inti with a 
new currency 
fujimori proposes allowing prices for subsidized goods and 
services to reach market levels but then would freeze wages and 
prices for six months he also promises to reach agreement with 
foreign lenders on new credits 
he has rejected help from the us military with the antidrug 
campaign and proposes to wean farmers from coca by stimulating 
production of legal crops 
vargas llosas inflation goal is 10 percent within a year and he 
wants fundamental changes in the economy based on freemarket 
principles 
the novelist would reduce the huge bureaucracy by shifting 
tens of thousands of workers to the private sector he proposes 
lifting price controls selling state enterprises and changing labor 
laws to allow companies to fire unproductive workers 
