mexico and increase mexican oil shipments to the central american 
country by 50 percent 
salvadoran president alfredo cristiani told a news conference 
that el salvador is behind in debt payments but gave few details on 
the restructuring program 
he did say however the negotiations involve more mexican 
investments in el salvador 
the increase in oil sales from 8000 to 12000 barrels a day 
comes under a 1981 pact under which mexico and venezuela sell oil to 
countries in the region at low interest with longterm credit 
other agreements that were signed saturday cover cooperation in 
education industrial development and radio and television 
relations between the two countries have been strained since 
1980 when mexico withdrew its ambassador to protest the killing of 
a mexican journalist in 1981 mexico and france signed a joint 
declaration recognizing the leftist rebels in el salvador as a 
political force 
mexico did not return its ambassador to san salvador until 1985 
the guerrillas continue to maintain a political office in mexico 
and their leaders hold frequent news conferences in mexico city 
at a news conference cristiani said he was optimistic that a 
peace agreement ending the 10yearold civil war in his country 
would be signed with the guerrillas by the end of this year 
we believe that before september a ceasefire can be signed and 
that in the following months a lasting peace can be signed with the 
integration of the fmln into the political life of the country as a 
political party and with full guarantees he said 
the fmln is the farabundo marti national liberation front the 
umbrella group for five guerrilla factions fighting to overthrow the 
usbacked government 
cristiani said the army could be reduced with the signing of a 
peace accord 
if that is achieved our army definitely will be able to be 
reduced considerably and the armed forces will be dedicated 
exclusively to safeguarding the integrity and sovereignty of el 
salvador he said 
he did not indicate how many of the nations 54000 government 
troops could be demobilized 
the government and guerrillas renewed talks in april agreeing on 
an agenda for negotiations 
more than 71000 people most of them civilians have been killed 
in the war between leftist guerrillas and a succession of 
usbacked governments 
</TEXT>
