canadas leaders signed a tentative deal saturday 
night to rescue a flagging constitutional accord that would grant 
special status to frenchspeaking quebec 
newfoundlands premier clyde wells said he remained 
dissatisfied with the compromise but may submit it for a popular 
referendum in his province 
however wells signed the agreement with the nine other 
provincial premiers in a nationally televised public session 
saturday night 
this is a happy day for canada declared prime minister 
brian mulroney before signing the document 
the agreement was worked out in ottawa at the end of the seventh 
day of private talks aimed at persuading holdout provinces to 
approve the package 
even if ratified the constitutional amendment recognizing 
quebec as a distinct society clause would have no immediate 
practical effect however it would oblige the supreme court to 
consider the provinces distinctiveness when considering specific 
laws challenged under the constitution 
it is also a symbol of enormous significance to frenchspeaking 
quebecers 
it was a great exercise in nation building said ontario 
premier david peterson after the accord was achieved there was 
blood in the floor but it was common blood 
but wells declared i am not approving of this particular 
accord 
he said he may submit it to a popular or legislative referendum 
in his province before the june 23 ratification deadline 
new brunswick premier frank mckenna who had been another 
holdout until the latest talks called the compromise the best 
deal possible 
quebec premier robert bourassa initially boycotted the talks 
saturday after refusing to discuss any more changes in the clause 
that would recognize quebec as a distinct society however 
later in the day he returned to the talks 
the tentative agreement would leave the distinctsociety clause 
unaltered but ask constitutional experts to prepare a legal opinion 
on how it would affect the countrys rights charter 
bourassa said of the final compromise this is not affecting 
the integrity of the meech lake accord we are quite satisfied that 
our objectives are fulfilled 
in announcing the agreement peterson said it must still be 
approved by the legislatures of newfoundland and new brunswick as 
well as a third holdout manitoba 
mulroney convened the 10 provincial leaders for the private 
talks because they face a june 23 deadline for ratification of the 
amendment to the 1982 canadian constitution 
quebec refused to sign the constitution saying it did not take 
the provinces distinct french character into consideration in an 
effort to win quebecs support the amendment known as the meech 
lake accord contains the clause that designates quebec a 
distinct society 
the other points in meech lake include expanding the provinces 
powers to opt out of some federalprovincial spending programs and 
a new constitutional amending formula 
bourassa of quebec has made no direct threats regarding 
separatism if the accord is not approved but nationalism is on the 
rise in the province and there is a growing sentiment for either 
separation or some sort of independenceassociation arrangement 
with the rest of canada 
canada has 25 million residents but onefourth of them live in 
quebec 
in 1987 mulroney and the 10 premiers signed a fivepoint 
agreement for the meech lake constitutional amendment and set a 
threeyear deadline for ratification 
in the interim governments changed in newfoundland manitoba 
and new brunswick and the new premiers reneged on the signatures of 
their predecessors quebec had insisted the accord must be passed 
as is and that other concerns worrying some of the premiers such 
as senate reform can be discussed at a future constitutional 
conference 
