<TEXT>
its no longer unusual to see debtfinanced 
takeovers go bust soon after completion but some older deals have 
started to sour too which shows that buying with borrowed money 
carries risks that last for years 
rh macy amp co inc went private in a 374 billion leveraged 
buyout led by management in 1986 accomplished with bank loans and 
sales of junk bonds the risky highyield securities that financed 
the 80s takeover boom 
four years later the retailer is 567 billion in debt and 
after a disastrous christmas shopping season concerned creditors 
are looking over its shoulder 
greyhound lines inc the nations biggest intercity bus company 
was taken private in 1987 by an investor group that paid 350 
million and relied heavily on junk bonds for the purchase money 
last week greyhound which has been hit hard by a 
threemonthold drivers strike filed for bankruptcy court 
protection from creditors 
the investors who bought these companies years ago never expected 
to be in trouble at this late date what went wrong 
too much debt and not enough margin for error and unexpected 
problems the same things that have waylaid younger buyouts like 
campeau corps failed 1988 takeover of federated department stores 
inc 
highly leveraged deals like these are fine as long as things go 
well but as soon as things go even slightly bad the fallout 
doesnt take very long to occur said jerome e hass professor of 
managerial economics and finance at cornell universitys johnson 
graduate school of management 
these are deals that were exceedingly thin hass said 
so when macy suffered a loss at christmas and greyhounds fleet 
was stalled by labor problems the companies were short of cash 
needed to pay bills including hefty interest charges 
like many other highly leveraged firms macy and greyhound did 
not plan years ago for unexpected events 
you kind of know whats going to happen in the next year but 
five years hence you dont really know said robert w vishny a 
university of chicago graduate school of business finance professor 
it is a case where you are potentially setting yourself up for 
trouble vishny said 
some of the shortsightedness comes from overly optimistic sales 
earnings projections particularly for retailers 
walter loeb a retailing analyst and consultant said macy had 
budgeted for a 10 percent annual increase in sales but like the 
rest of the retail industry has fallen far short of the mark 
the greyhound and macy buyouts arent the only older deals to 
encounter rough sledding southland corp which went private in a 
49 billion leveraged buyout in 1987 recently said it was selling 
out to a japanese firm because it couldnt handle the debt load 
southland like macy and campeau is a retailer hit by declining 
sales that it did not forecast while it looks nice on paper most 
retailing lbos have had a detrimental effect on the companies 
loeb said 
but macy exacerbated its problems by making a big acquisition 
after its lbo 
macy spent more than 1 billion to buy two department store 
chains from campeau in 1988 after the two companies had fought one 
another in a monthlong takeover battle for federated 
ironically macy had bid more for federated than campeau which 
ended up paying 66 billion for the retailer plus another 22 
billion in expenses campeau was unable to handle its debt bill and 
ultimately ended up in bankruptcy court 
greyhound meanwhile spent 80 million several months after its 
own buyout to purchase assets of its competitor trailways lines inc 
in hindsight neither macy nor greyhound could really afford 
their new acquisitions 
greyhounds problems will be resolved in bankruptcy court the 
estimates are it will take six months to a year to reorganize the 
company 
macy meanwhile is expected to weather the storm on its own the 
companys latest quarterly earnings report issued last week 
reassured junk bond investors 
loeb said macy management especially company chairman edward 
finkelstein has kept an open line of communications to suppliers 
creditors and investors 
that was an asset loeb said 
 
</TEXT>
