<TEXT>
it was almost as if san franciscos 
legendary fog invaded the conference where banking authorities from 
22 nations were talking about the economic future of eastern europe 
the man responsible for sweeping changes there appeared in the same 
hotel but the bankers never saw him 
soviet president mikhail gorbachev failed to take advantage of 
the gathering of some of the worlds most powerful commerical and 
government bank officials at the international monetary conference 
this past week instead he tried to drum up investment from 
california business leaders 
organizers of the annual gathering of about 200 bankers said they 
spoke to soviet embassy officials in washington about scheduling an 
appearance by gorbachev who stopped in california after his summit 
with president bush but the bankers never received a reply 
several conference participants said they believed the soviet 
leader blew an important opportunity to discuss his nations need 
for investment with those holding the keys to the vaults 
but an address by gorbachev to the bankers may have fallen on 
deaf ears anyway several prominent conference participants said the 
soviet union has a long way to go in restructuring its economy 
before western financiers would feel comfortable investing there 
at a news conference top officials of the central banks of 
japan england france and the united states were asked what lessons 
they had learned from their large loans to south america in the 
1970s many of which have gone sour 
jacques de larosiere governor of the bank of france said the 
principal lesson is that a nation must have made substantial 
capitalist economic reforms to be considered a suitable candidate 
for bank loans 
larosiere said mexico was a good example of a borrower that has 
taken such major steps as selling off governmentowned industry and 
loosening regulation of business he said the west must press 
eastern europe to enact similar reforms 
that thought was echoed by us treasury secretary nicholas brady 
in an address before the bankers 
the countries that move forcefully to privatize stateowned 
operations to open trading and investment regimes and to withdraw 
the government from the marketplace will be the ones tht attract the 
capital to fuel growth brady said 
takeshi ohta a deputy governor of the bank of japan said loans 
by governmentsponsored banks such as the world bank may be needed 
before private banks feel secure in committing their money to the 
former communist nations 
but brady indicated that little additional aid to eastern europe 
would come from the us government he told the bankers that they 
must be willing to lend money to these countries despite concerns 
about credit risk 
as more countries embrace the principles of economic freedom 
creditors will need to stand ready to lend their support he said 
you in this room cannot simply be bystanders to this process 
two former top government financial officials said the us 
should do its part to free up capital needed by eastern europe by 
trimming the federal deficit which is financed by treasury 
borrowing that could be going elsewhere 
former federal reserve board chairman paul volcker told the 
bankers that the united states must curb domestic spending both 
public and private according to a text of his remarks in the 
closeddoor sessions 
volcker also said that nations particularly the united states 
must take steps to increase the rate of savings which will boost 
the amount of money available for borrowing by the former soviet 
bloc 
nigel lawson former chancellor of the exchequer in great 
britain seconded volckers plea for greater private savings 
he said governments must stop draining away investment funds by 
running budget deficits according to a copy of his remarks lawson 
did not specifically mention the united states 
in other business and economic developments this past week 
bankruptcy court was the forum for more debtdistressed 
companies greyhound lines sought chapter 11 protection from 
creditors partly the result of a prolonged strike ames department 
stores inc said it would close nearly a third of its 679 outlets 
reflecting the discounters efforts to dump moneylosing operations 
since seeking bankruptcy court refuge in april 
conagra inc will acquire beatrice co for 134 billion from 
kohlberg kravis roberts amp co the deal represents the last chunk of 
what had been a much larger beatrice bought by kohlberg in 1986 and 
will make conagra one of the worlds biggest food companies 
general motors corp outdid competitors and won a 1 billion 
fiveyear agreement to supply parts to the soviet unions auto 
industry the deal is one of the largest by a western company in the 
east bloc 
flamboyant developer donald j trump faced growing pressure from 
lenders feeling queasy about his debtridden complex of casinos 
hotels and other property despite increased speculation that trump 
will be forced to sell assets in order to pay bills aides said none 
of his atlantic city hotels were for sale 
